<!-- END APPRAISAL FORM -->
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      The school catchments in and around Manly West are a primary draw for family buyers in the eastern corridor. Families who have been researching school options while comparing suburbs in this part of Brisbane have typically identified the catchments on offer here as a key reason to make the move east. When a family buyer has committed to a school catchment, they arrive at your open home as a motivated buyer who has already resolved the most important question in their decision-making process: all that remains is finding the right property.
    </p>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      The housing stock in Manly West includes a mix of post-war brick homes, low-set family homes from the 1970s and 1980s, and a growing number of renovated and updated properties that reflect the suburb's ongoing appeal to family buyers who see long-term value in the eastern bayside location. Blocks are generally competitive relative to the price point, with outdoor spaces that suit family living. The suburb is not a prestige address in the way that Manly proper is, but it delivers consistent owner-occupier demand from buyers who understand what the eastern corridor offers and have made a deliberate decision to be part of it.
    </p>
    <div style="display:flex; gap:1.5rem; flex-wrap:wrap;">
